The UI freezes for two full seconds every time a user uploads a spreadsheet. The computation itself only takes 400 milliseconds. The other 1.6 seconds is the browser waiting for the main thread to become available for anything else at all.
A feature parses a large CSV file client-side, validates every row, and computes summary statistics before displaying a preview. For a small file, this happens instantly. For a file with tens of thousands of rows, the entire browser tab freezes: the page stops responding to clicks, scrolling stutters or stops entirely, and any animation on the page visibly pauses, for as long as the parsing and computation take to complete, because all of it runs on the same single thread responsible for rendering the page and responding to every user interaction.
JavaScript’s single-threaded execution model is usually described as a simplifying feature (no locks, no race conditions between threads, one clear execution order). It becomes a genuine liability the moment any single piece of work takes long enough to visibly block everything else happening on that same thread, which includes not just your application’s other JavaScript but the browser’s own rendering and input-handling work. Web Workers exist specifically to solve this, by running JavaScript on a genuinely separate thread, and understanding both what they solve and what they don’t is the actual prerequisite to using them effectively.
Why “just optimize the function” often isn’t enough
The instinctive first response to a slow, blocking computation is to make the computation itself faster: better algorithms, fewer allocations, more efficient data structures. This genuinely helps, and it’s worth doing regardless, but it doesn’t address the structural problem: as long as the computation runs on the main thread at all, any amount of synchronous work beyond a few milliseconds blocks user interaction for its entire duration, no matter how well-optimized that work is. A perfectly optimized 400-millisecond computation still produces 400 milliseconds of a frozen, unresponsive tab if it runs on the main thread. Optimization reduces the freeze’s duration, but a Web Worker removes the freeze from the main thread’s experience entirely, moving the computation to run genuinely in parallel with continued page responsiveness.
// Blocks the main thread for the computation's entire duration, however long that is
function processLargeCsv(fileContents) {
const rows = parseCSV(fileContents);
const validated = rows.map(validateRow);
const stats = computeStatistics(validated);
return { validated, stats };
}Moving the work to a Web Worker
A Web Worker runs in a genuinely separate execution context, with its own global scope, no access to the DOM, and communication with the main thread happening exclusively through message passing. This isolation is what makes true parallelism safe, since the worker can never directly touch anything the main thread is simultaneously rendering or manipulating.
// csv-worker.js - runs on a separate thread
self.onmessage = function (event) {
const { fileContents } = event.data;
const rows = parseCSV(fileContents);
const validated = rows.map(validateRow);
const stats = computeStatistics(validated);
self.postMessage({ validated, stats });
};javascript
// Main thread - dispatches work and stays responsive while it runs
function processLargeCsvOffMainThread(fileContents) {
return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
const worker = new Worker("csv-worker.js"); worker.onmessage = (event) => {
resolve(event.data);
worker.terminate(); // Clean up once done; don't leave the worker thread running idle.
};
worker.onerror = (err) => {
reject(err);
worker.terminate();
};
worker.postMessage({ fileContents });
});
}
While the worker processes the file, the main thread remains completely free to handle clicks, render updates, and run animations. The exact freeze described in this article’s opening example simply doesn’t happen, because the expensive computation is no longer competing with the main thread’s rendering and input-handling responsibilities at all.
The real cost of message passing: data has to be copied or transferred
Communication between the main thread and a worker happens through postMessage, and by default, the data passed is cloned (using the structured clone algorithm), not shared by reference. For large datasets, this cloning cost is real and worth accounting for explicitly, since a naive implementation can end up spending a meaningful fraction of the total time budget on copying data back and forth rather than on the actual computation.
javascript
// Cloning a large array both into and out of the worker - real, measurable overhead for big datasets
worker.postMessage({ hugeArray }); // cloned on the way in
self.postMessage({ processedHugeArray }); // cloned again on the way outFor genuinely large binary data (a large file’s raw bytes, a big typed array of numeric data), Transferable objects avoid this cloning cost entirely by transferring ownership of the underlying memory buffer directly to the worker, rather than copying it, at the cost of the main thread losing access to that data until it’s transferred back.
javascript
const buffer = new ArrayBuffer(largeSize);
worker.postMessage({ buffer }, [buffer]); // transfers ownership, zero-copy
// `buffer` is now unusable on the main thread until the worker transfers it backFor structured data that isn’t naturally a binary buffer (a large array of parsed row objects, for instance), this transfer optimization doesn’t directly apply, and the cloning cost of postMessage needs to be weighed against the benefit of offloading the computation. For genuinely large structured datasets, it's sometimes worth restructuring the data into a more transfer-friendly binary format (a typed array with a fixed schema) specifically to take advantage of zero-copy transfer, if the computation is expensive enough and the dataset large enough that cloning overhead would otherwise eat meaningfully into the benefit gained from offloading in the first place.
Worker pools: reusing workers instead of spinning up a new one per task
Creating a new Worker instance has real startup overhead (loading and parsing the worker script, initializing its execution context), which is wasteful to repeat for every individual small task if a page needs to offload many separate pieces of work over its lifetime, rather than a single one-off computation like the CSV example above.
javascript
class WorkerPool {
constructor(workerScript, poolSize = navigator.hardwareConcurrency || 4) {
this.workers = Array.from(
{ length: poolSize },
() => new Worker(workerScript)
);
this.queue = [];
this.availableWorkers = [...this.workers];
} runTask(data) {
return new Promise((resolve) => {
this.queue.push({ data, resolve });
this._processQueue();
});
}
_processQueue() {
while (this.queue.length > 0 && this.availableWorkers.length > 0) {
const worker = this.availableWorkers.pop();
const { data, resolve } = this.queue.shift();
worker.onmessage = (event) => {
resolve(event.data);
this.availableWorkers.push(worker);
this._processQueue(); // Pick up the next queued task, if any.
};
worker.postMessage(data);
}
}
}
Sizing the pool based on navigator.hardwareConcurrency (the number of logical CPU cores available) is a reasonable default. Creating meaningfully more workers than available cores doesn't provide additional real parallelism, since the underlying hardware can only genuinely execute as many threads simultaneously as it has cores, and additional workers beyond that point just compete with each other for the same limited CPU resources rather than adding genuine throughput.
When a Web Worker is the wrong tool
Not every slow operation benefits from a Web Worker, and it’s worth being explicit about the cases where it doesn’t help or actively adds unnecessary complexity. DOM manipulation cannot happen inside a worker at all: workers have no access to document or any DOM API, so any task requiring DOM reads or writes needs to stay on the main thread regardless of how expensive it is; the earlier article on layout thrashing covers optimizing exactly this category of main-thread-bound work. Network requests don't need a worker: fetch is already asynchronous and non-blocking on the main thread by design, so moving a network call into a worker provides no benefit, since the main thread was never blocked waiting on it in the first place. Small, fast computations (anything comfortably under a few milliseconds) aren't worth the message-passing overhead and worker creation cost, which can, for sufficiently small tasks, actually exceed the cost of just running the computation directly and briefly on the main thread.
The right candidates are specifically synchronous, CPU-bound computations that take long enough (generally tens of milliseconds or more) to visibly affect responsiveness if run on the main thread: data parsing and transformation, image or video processing, complex calculations, client-side search or filtering across large datasets, and cryptographic operations.
Comlink: removing the message-passing boilerplate
The raw postMessage/onmessage API, while foundational, produces verbose, callback-heavy code for anything beyond a single simple request-response exchange. Comlink, a small library from the Chrome team, wraps this in a Proxy-based API that lets worker functions be called as if they were regular async functions, hiding the message-passing entirely.
// worker.js
import { expose } from "comlink";const api = {
processLargeCsv(fileContents) {
const rows = parseCSV(fileContents);
return { validated: rows.map(validateRow), stats: computeStatistics(rows) };
},
};
expose(api);
// main thread
import { wrap } from "comlink";
const worker = new Worker("worker.js", { type: "module" });
const workerApi = wrap(worker);
const result = await workerApi.processLargeCsv(fileContents); // reads like a normal async callThis meaningfully reduces the boilerplate and cognitive overhead of adopting workers for more than the simplest one-off task, and it’s worth reaching for once a codebase has more than a couple of distinct worker interactions to manage, since the raw message-passing API’s verbosity compounds quickly across multiple different task types each needing their own request/response message shape handled manually.
Measuring the actual improvement, not just assuming it
As with any performance optimization, it’s worth confirming the Web Worker migration actually improved the metric that matters (main thread responsiveness during the operation) rather than assuming it did simply because the computation moved off-thread. The Long Tasks API directly measures periods where the main thread was blocked for more than 50 milliseconds, which is precisely the symptom this optimization targets.
const observer = new PerformanceObserver((list) => {
for (const entry of list.getEntries()) {
metrics.histogram("long_task_duration_ms", entry.duration);
}
});observer.observe({ entryTypes: ["longtask"] });
Comparing long task frequency and duration before and after moving a specific computation to a worker gives direct, measured confirmation of the improvement, rather than relying on a subjective sense that the page “feels” more responsive, which is a reasonable initial signal but not a substitute for an actual before-and-after measurement using the browser’s own instrumentation for exactly this purpose.
SharedArrayBuffer: true shared memory, with real security caveats
For cases where even Transferable objects’ one-way ownership transfer is too limiting (genuinely concurrent access to the same memory from both the main thread and one or more workers simultaneously), SharedArrayBuffer provides actual shared memory both sides can read and write concurrently, backed by Atomics for safe, race-condition-free coordination over that shared memory.
